    "jobDescription": "QiCAP.Ai (QI-CAP Investments Private Limited) is one of India's largest quantitative investment firms, deploying high-frequency trading strategies across asset classes in Indian markets. Our in-house engineers and mathematicians build proprietary technology and quantitative models powering execution strategies for professional traders and investment solutions for family offices. Role Overview We are hiring engineers to work across our technology stack from data pipelines and applied ML research to the full-stack tooling, real-time risk systems, and ultra-low- latency infrastructure that power live trading. This is a hands-on, high-ownership environment where the systems you build are measured against real capital, in production, every day. We hire coders, not branches! If you're a strong competitive programmer with solid Codeforces or CodeChef ratings, we want to hear from you, no matter what your degree is! What You'll Work On Designing and optimizing data pipelines and ML/AI models on large-scale, high-frequency market data Building full-stack internal tools and trader-facing interfaces Writing modern C++ (17/20) on latency-critical paths  order entry, market- data decoding, matching-adjacent logic Implementing real-time risk and PnL systems in Go/Rust that gate whether an order reaches the market Digital design and HDL work (Verilog/System Verilog) on FPGA for tick-to- trade paths, where relevant Required Skills Strong CS fundamentals: data structures, algorithms, operating systems, computer architecture, networks Ability to reason about what the machine is actually doing, not just what the code says Depth in at least one of: Python, C++, Go, Rust, or an HDL (Verilog/VHDL) Comfort in Linux and on the command line; instinct to measure before optimizing Evidence of things you've built under real constraints and debugged when they broke  systems projects, competitive programming, open source, production reality Good to Have Statistics, ML/AI, and large-dataset handling Full-stack development (Golang preferred) Low-latency systems: lock-free concurrency, NUMA-aware structures, kernel- bypass networking (Solar flare Onload, DPDK) Digital design fundamentals: pipelining, timing closure, clock domains Distributed systems, CI/CD, observability Nobody arrives knowing all of this and we don't expect you to. We hire for fundamentals and slope: how fast you go from 'I've never seen this' to 'I own it.' The rest, we teach",
